discoverers.name: Thales
discoverers.contribution: The first to describe the Earth as a spherical object and the idea of its rotation on its axis.

discoverers.name: Nikolai Copernicus
discoverers.contribution: Developed the heliocentric theory, according to which the Sun is at the center and the planets revolve around it.

discoverers.name: Galileo Galilei
discoverers.contribution: Performed important observations and experiments, proving the validity of the heliocentric theory and making numerous significant discoveries related to the movement of Earth and other planets.

discoverers.name: Percival Lowell
discoverers.contribution: Conducted extensive studies and observations of Mars, popularizing the idea of canals and intelligent life on the planet.

discoverers.name: Friedrich Bessel
discoverers.contribution: Contributed to the accurate measurement of star positions and the development of celestial mechanics.

discoverers.name: Robert Hooke
discoverers.contribution: Made important contributions to astronomy, including the study of lunar craters and the development of the compound microscope.

discoverers.name: Johann Bayer
discoverers.contribution: Known for his star atlas Uranometria, which cataloged over 1,000 stars and introduced the Bayer designation system for naming stars.

discoverers.name: Robert Innes
discoverers.contribution: Discovered Proxima Centauri, the closest known star to the Solar System, and made significant contributions to the study of double stars.
